{"cursor":"9910","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"]] A 'wax tablet' is a tablet made of wood and covered with a layer of wax,\noften linked loosely to a cover tablet, as a \"double-leaved\" diptych. It was\nused as a reusable and portable writing surface in Antiquity and throughout the\nMiddle Ages. Cicero's letters make passing reference to the use of cerae, and\nsome examples of wax-tablets have been preserved in waterlogged deposits in the\nRoman fort at Vindolanda on Hadrian's Wall. Medieval wax tablet books are on\ndisplay in several European museums.\n","linknr":221,"url":"Wax_tablet","recorded":1364154376,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Wax_tablet&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Wax_tablet&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Wachstafel_rem.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Wachstafel_rem.jpg/220px-Wachstafel_rem.jpg","/wiki/File:Wachstafel_rem.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Stylus","/wiki/Tablet_(disambiguation)","/wiki/Wax","/wiki/Diptych","/wiki/Writing","/wiki/Classical_antiquity","/wiki/Middle_Ages","/wiki/Cicero","/wiki/Roman_Britain","/wiki/Vindolanda","/wiki/Hadrian